        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-05-12T11:03:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-05-12T11:03:00-05:00" n="68"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d68">
                <head>68. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Secretary of State, at Paris</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d68fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 663.001/5–1255. Secret; <gloss target="#t_niact1"
                        >Niact</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1955-05-12T11:03:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 12, 1955—11:03 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 24. Eyes only Secretary from the
                    President. Thank you very much for keeping me so completely informed. Your
                    cables are intensely interesting.</p>
                <pb facs="0132" n="106" xml:id="pg_106"/>
                <p>I fully approve your courses of action in regard to the Austrian Treaty, though I
                    am of course hopeful that the situation will so develop that it will be possible
                    for us to participate in the final signing of the document in Vienna with the
                    other powers over the coming weekend.<note n="2" xml:id="d68fn2">
                        <p>At 9 p.m. on May 12 Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DAW1"
                                >Dulles</persName> replied:</p>
                        <p>“I greatly appreciate your personal message. I think the situation has
                            now developed so that we can sign the Austrian Treaty on Sunday. The
                            Soviets have given way, and I am proceeding to Vienna tomorrow morning.”
                                (<gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 36 from Paris; <hi
                                rend="italic">ibid.</hi>)</p>
                    </note> Warm regard, DE.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HHJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Hoover</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
